---
import LocationLayout from '../../layouts/LocationLayout.astro';
import { marsLocations } from '../../data/marsLocations';

const location = marsLocations.find(loc => loc.id === 'planum-boreum');
if (!location) {
  throw new Error('Planum Boreum location not found');
}
---

<LocationLayout title="Planum Boreum - North Polar Ice Cap" location={location}>
  <!-- Hero Image Section -->
  <div class="mb-8">
    <div
      class="relative h-96 bg-gradient-to-r from-blue-900 to-cyan-700 rounded-lg overflow-hidden"
    >
      <div class="absolute inset-0 bg-black/20"></div>
      <div class="absolute bottom-6 left-6 text-white">
        <p class="text-sm opacity-80">
          Mars north polar ice cap layered deposits and spiral troughs
        </p>
        <p class="text-xs opacity-60">NASA/JPL-Caltech/MSSS</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>

  <!-- Overview Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Overview</h2>
    <div class="grid lg:grid-cols-3 gap-8">
      <div class="lg:col-span-2">
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          Planum Boreum, Mars' north polar ice cap, represents one of the largest 
          water reservoirs on the Red Planet. This massive dome-shaped structure 
          extends approximately 1,000 kilometers in diameter and rises up to 3 
          kilometers above the surrounding terrain, containing enough water ice 
          to cover the entire planet with a 1.5-meter layer if melted.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
          The ice cap consists of layered deposits that preserve millions of years 
          of Martian climate history, with alternating layers of water ice and dust 
          that record ancient climate cycles. These polar layered deposits make up 
          the majority of the ice cap's volume and offer scientists an unprecedented 
          archive of Mars' atmospheric evolution.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Recent 2024 research has revealed that the ice cap is currently 
          undergoing active retreat through ice block falls and mass wasting, 
          providing new insights into how Mars' water cycle continues to shape 
          the planet's polar regions in the present day.
        </p>
      </div>

      <!-- Quick Facts Sidebar -->
      <div class="bg-gray-800/50 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">Quick Facts</h3>
        <div class="space-y-3">
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Diameter:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~1,000 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Maximum Thickness:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~3 km</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Water Ice Volume:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">~1.1 million km³</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Composition:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">95% water ice, 5% dust</span>
          </div>
          <div>
            <span class="text-gray-400 text-sm">Climate Record:</span>
            <span class="text-white block">Millions of years</span>
          </div>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Ice Structure Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Layered Ice Architecture
    </h2>
    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-8 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The north polar ice cap's structure reveals a complex history of climate 
        change on Mars. The layered deposits extend up to 2 kilometers thick and 
        consist of alternating bands of relatively clean water ice and dusty ice 
        layers, each recording different periods of Martian atmospheric conditions.
      </p>
      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-3 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Seasonal Cap</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            A thin layer of CO₂ frost that forms each winter and sublimates during 
            summer, driving the planet's seasonal atmospheric pressure changes.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Residual Cap</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The permanent water ice core that persists year-round, containing the 
            vast majority of the ice cap's water reserves.
          </p>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Basal Unit</h4>
          <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
            The foundation layer composed of sand and dust cemented by water ice, 
            forming the base upon which the layered deposits accumulated.
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Water Cycle Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Mars Water Cycle Engine
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-blue-900/50 to-blue-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-blue-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Seasonal Water Exchange
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Each Martian summer, the north polar ice cap releases significant amounts 
          of water vapor into the atmosphere, driving global water transport. This 
          seasonal sublimation creates atmospheric humidity that can travel to 
          other parts of Mars, including the equatorial regions.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          The water vapor can condense and precipitate as frost at night or during 
          winter, creating a planet-wide water cycle centered on the polar ice caps.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-cyan-900/50 to-cyan-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-cyan-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Climate History Archive
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The layered structure preserves evidence of Mars' orbital variations 
          and climate shifts over millions of years. Each layer represents 
          different atmospheric dust concentrations and ice accumulation rates.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          Scientists can read these layers like tree rings, revealing periods 
          of dust storms, atmospheric thickness changes, and water availability.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Recent Discoveries Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Recent Scientific Breakthroughs
    </h2>

    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6 mb-8">
      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-red-900/50 to-red-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-red-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Active Ice Cap Retreat (2024)
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          Groundbreaking 2024 research published in Nature Communications revealed 
          that the north polar ice cap is actively retreating through ongoing 
          mass wasting processes. Ice block falls are intensive at the marginal 
          steep scarps, causing asymmetric retreat of the ice cap.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          This discovery quantifies current water ice loss and provides evidence 
          of basal unit undercutting effects, showing that Mars' climate is still 
          actively reshaping its polar regions.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div
        class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/50 to-green-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
      >
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          SHARAD Radar Discoveries
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm mb-4">
          The SHARAD radar sounder aboard Mars Reconnaissance Orbiter has mapped 
          the base of the north polar cap 1.5-2 km beneath the surface, revealing 
          the true extent of water ice reserves and internal structure.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 text-sm">
          These observations confirmed that the ice cap contains approximately 
          55% water ice by volume, with enough water to cover Mars with a 
          1.5-meter global ocean if melted.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
      <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
        Spiral Trough Formation
      </h3>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
        The ice cap's distinctive spiral trough patterns, visible from orbit, 
        are formed by katabatic winds flowing down from the ice cap's center. 
        These troughs expose the internal layered structure and provide natural 
        cross-sections for studying the ice cap's composition and history.
      </p>
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
        Recent analysis suggests these troughs are actively maintained by 
        wind erosion and sublimation processes, making them dynamic features 
        that continue to evolve under current Martian conditions.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Terraforming Potential Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Terraforming Assessment
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-green-900/30 to-green-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-green-700/50"
    >
      <div class="flex items-center mb-6">
        <div
          class="w-12 h-12 bg-green-600 rounded-full flex items-center justify-center mr-4"
        >
          <span class="text-white font-bold text-xl">9</span>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h3 class="text-2xl font-semibold text-white">
            Exceptional Terraforming Potential
          </h3>
          <p class="text-green-300">
            Massive water reserves and climate regulation capabilities
          </p>
        </div>
      </div>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Advantages</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Largest accessible water reservoir on Mars</li>
            <li>• Natural climate regulation through water cycle</li>
            <li>• Existing atmospheric water transport system</li>
            <li>• Layered structure ideal for mining operations</li>
            <li>• Evidence of ongoing geological processes</li>
            <li>• Rich climate history for understanding Mars</li>
            <li>• Potential for large-scale water extraction</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">Challenges</h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Extreme polar temperatures (-150°C to -70°C)</li>
            <li>• Limited solar radiation for energy generation</li>
            <li>• Extreme seasonal day/night cycles</li>
            <li>• Active ice retreat and instability</li>
            <li>• Difficult access and harsh conditions</li>
            <li>• Dust accumulation in equipment</li>
            <li>• Radiation exposure at high latitudes</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Resource Utilization Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      In-Situ Resource Utilization
    </h2>
    <div class="space-y-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Water Extraction Potential
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-4">
          The north polar ice cap represents the most significant water resource 
          for future Mars missions. With relatively pure water ice accessible 
          near the surface through the exposed layers in spiral troughs, 
          extraction operations could provide water for drinking, agriculture, 
          and industrial processes.
        </p>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Water can also be electrolyzed to produce oxygen for life support 
          and hydrogen for rocket fuel, making the polar ice caps crucial 
          infrastructure for Mars exploration and settlement.
        </p>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-xl font-semibold text-white mb-4">
          Atmospheric Engineering Implications
        </h3>
        <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed">
          Any terraforming efforts on Mars would need to carefully consider 
          the polar ice caps' role in the planet's water cycle. While melting 
          the ice caps could provide atmospheric water vapor, their current 
          function as climate regulators and seasonal water sources makes 
          them valuable in their present state for supporting life across Mars.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- Future Exploration Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">
      Future Exploration Opportunities
    </h2>
    <div
      class="bg-gradient-to-br from-purple-900/30 to-purple-800/20 p-8 rounded-lg border border-purple-700/50"
    >
      <p class="text-gray-300 leading-relaxed mb-6">
        The north polar ice cap remains one of the highest priority targets 
        for future Mars exploration. Understanding its structure, dynamics, 
        and accessibility will be crucial for planning sustainable human 
        presence on Mars and unlocking the planet's water resources.
      </p>

      <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Proposed Mission Objectives
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Deep ice core drilling for climate history</li>
            <li>• Characterization of spiral trough dynamics</li>
            <li>• Water ice purity and accessibility mapping</li>
            <li>• Long-term monitoring of ice cap retreat</li>
            <li>• Assessment of extraction technologies</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
        <div>
          <h4 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-3">
            Technological Requirements
          </h4>
          <ul class="space-y-2 text-gray-300 text-sm">
            <li>• Cold-weather operational capabilities</li>
            <li>• Automated drilling and sampling systems</li>
            <li>• Long-range transportation methods</li>
            <li>• Extended power systems for polar night</li>
            <li>• Advanced radar and imaging technology</li>
          </ul>
        </div>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>

  <!-- External Resources Section -->
  <section class="mb-12">
    <h2 class="text-3xl font-bold text-white mb-6 font-display">Learn More</h2>
    <div class="grid md:grid-cols-2 gap-6">
      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">NASA Resources</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/resource/stratigraphy-of-the-north-polar-deposits/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Stratigraphy of North Polar Deposits
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://marsed.asu.edu/mep/ice/polar-caps/planum-boreum"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mars Education - North Polar Ice Cap
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://science.nasa.gov/resource/the-changing-ice-cap-of-mars/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              The Changing Ice Cap of Mars
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>

      <div class="bg-gray-800/30 p-6 rounded-lg border border-gray-700">
        <h3 class="text-lg font-semibold text-white mb-4">Recent Research</h3>
        <ul class="space-y-2">
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://www.nature.com/articles/s41467-025-56018-2"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Mass Wasting and Ice Cap Retreat (2024)
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://faculty.dartmouth.edu/artsandsciences/news/2024/08/ice-caps-mars-offer-clues-ancient-climates"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              Ice Caps Offer Clues to Ancient Climates
            </a>
          </li>
          <li>
            <a
              href="https://pmc.ncbi.nlm.nih.gov/articles/PMC5791158/"
              class="text-blue-400 hover:text-blue-300 text-sm"
              target="_blank"
              rel="noopener noreferrer"
            >
              3-D Imaging Using Orbital Radar Data
            </a>
          </li>
        </ul>
      </div>
    </div>
  </section>
</LocationLayout>